column10:
Risk of rain Returns is a polished risk of rain 1 with proper multiplayer, new content, QOL changes and a coat of paint, that is about it. 
{Edit: my review was initially negative due to the way they handled aiming, since then they have given the bare minimum of allowing the character to aim using the mouse position still just left and right however}

It keeps a lot of the things that I would consider issues and flaws in risk of rain 1, if you like risk of rain 1 you will love this game, if you're a risk of rain 2 player, you may not get what you wanted to out of this. There appears to be no scrappers or printers unfortunate considering that was the something that made ror2 stand above other roguelikes, the movement is, well is limiting in comparison to ror2 (I know it's 2d but that doesn't mean it can't be improved upon), I've played quite a bit of ror1 I should care to mention and it never quite stuck with me due to how janky things like falling and shooting feel, I went in expecting a fine tuned experience something more akin to its sequel, risk of rain 1 but with new mechanics, but its kinda just the first game with a visual upgrade, rule changes and new content, QOL changes. 

I feel like a kid lost in a walmart playing this, there doesn't seem to be a map button (correct me if I'm wrong), the map is massive and i just feel so lost and for how big it is, i feel like there should be more items with how massive the map is (i never had this issue in the first risk of rain or it's sequel). {Edit: i no longer found this as much of an issue, but it's worth considering.}

I like its remastered music, I like how polished the game feels in aspects such as characters shooting or moving, the environments are significantly better drawn and designed...

that's all I can really say considering my playtime, just buy it if you are a major risk of rain 1 fan, even to a risk of rain 2 fan its {definitely} worth considering, just go in open minded.

The rain is back and is better than ever.

We get everything from the first installment with few new stuffs including some from the second:
- survivors, items, even alt skills.
- game rules tuning whether you prefer some from the original or the sequel, like not having to kill everything before entering the portal--which is turned on by default, [i]thank god[/i];
- even more difficulty adjustments for giga-tryhards and babies alike; 
- challenge mode mini-stages to skip grinding for unlockables (well tbf some are locked solely behind this one);
- prettier UI;
- much MUCH better online multiplayer experience;
- and more

Soundtrack-wise I honestly can't really tell any difference from a glance, maybe you would if you directly compared them side-by-side. Or hey they're on spotify maybe go check em out or something idk
